<worksheet>
    <title>LT 12 Exponentials and Logs as Inverses</title>
<objectives>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
              Recognize exponentials and log graphs as inverses  
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Use log properties to evaluate logs.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Convert between exponentials and logs (both ways).
            </p>
        </li>
        
    </ul>
</objectives>
<exercise>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Reveiwing Inverses:
        </p>
        <p>
            We know that the domain of <m>f(x)</m> is the _____________ of <m>f^{-1}(x)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We know that the range of <m>f(x)</m> is the ____________ of <m>f^{-1}(x)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We know if <m>f^{-1}(x)</m> contains the point (3, -7), then the inverse point on <m>f(x)</m> is (_____,_____).
        </p>
        <p>
           We know that inverses "undo" each other.  Such as addition undoing ________ and division undoing ___________. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<introduction>
    <p>
        We will be graphing equations in Desmos, and creating a rough sketch on the grid provided.  Enter the equations given and determine if they are inverse equations.  Always have the line <m>y=x</m> graphed.
    </p>
</introduction>
<task workspace="0.01in">
    <statement>
        <p>
           Graph <m>y=x+5</m> and <m> y=x-5</m>.  Are the two equations inverses?  Explain your thinking. 
        </p>
         <image source="2x2grid.png" width="40%">
            <shortdescription>2x2 blank grid</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
    <statement>
        <p>
           Graph <m>y=9x+1</m> and <m> y=9x-1</m>.  Are the two equations inverses?  Explain your thinking. 
        </p>
         <image source="2x2grid.png" width="40%">
            <shortdescription>2x2 blank grid</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
    <statement>
        <p>
           Graph <m>y=10^x</m> and <m></m>. log(x) Are the two equations inverses?  Explain your thinking. 
        </p> 
        <image source="2x2grid.png" width="40%">
            <shortdescription>2x2 blank grid</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
    <statement>
        <p>
           Graph <m>y=4^x</m> and <m> y=log_4(x)</m>.(write the equation y=log_4(x))  Are the two equations inverses?  Explain your thinking. 
        </p>
         <image source="2x2grid.png" width="40%">
            <shortdescription>2x2 blank grid</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
    <statement>
        <p>
           Graph <m>y=e^x</m> and <m> y=ln(x)</m>.  Are the two equations inverses?  Explain your thinking. 
        </p>
         <image source="2x2grid.png" width="40%">
            <shortdescription>2x2 blank grid</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </statement>
</task>
</exercise>
<exercise>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Use the following properties to evaluate the logs.  Remember: Logs are _______________.
        </p>
        </introduction>
        <task workspace="$1">
            <statement>
             <p> <m>log_b(1)=0</m>  </p>
            <p>Use what you know about exponent properties to explain why this is true.
        </p>   
            </statement>
        </task>
        
       <task workspace="0.01in">
        <statement>
            <p> 
            <m>log_b(b)=1</m>  </p>
            <p>Use what you know about exponent properties to explain why this is true.
        </p>                
            
        </statement>
       </task>
       <task workspace="0.01in">
        <statement>
           <p>
            <m>log_b(b^x)=x</m>  </p>
            <p>Use what you know about exponent properties to explain why this is true.
        </p>
        </statement>
       </task>
       
    
    <task workspace="0.01in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Evaluate the log <m>log_2(2^4)</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.01in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Evaluate the log <m>log_12(1)</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.01in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Evaluate the log <m>log_{\sqrt8}({\sqrt8})</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.01in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Evaluate the log <m>ln(e)</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<introduction>
<p>
    The most important phrase in learning logs is _______ are _________________.
</p>
<p>
    Keepoing this in mind, convert these logs and exponentials.
</p>
</introduction>
<task workspace="0.01in">
<statement>
    <p>
        <m>14^2=x</m>  as a log:
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
<statement>
    <p>
        <m>e^{0.7x}=4.05</m> as a natural log:
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
<statement>
    <p>
        <m>log_{0.5}(25)=x</m> as an exponential:
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task workspace="0.01in">
<statement>
    <p>
        <m>ln(e^x)=-3</m> as an exponential:
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
</exercise>
</worksheet>